<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n26090l"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n26" href="#n26090l">N26 (VI.B.18)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n26all.htm#n26090l"> 90(l)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> pravity</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Bishop Ralph of Shrewsbury has heard that the Prioress of Cannington received four women as sisters of that house for &pound;20 each, falling into the &ldquo;<mark>pravity</mark> of simony;&rdquo; William of Wykeham writes to the nuns of Romsey in 1387 that in our said visitations it was discovered and declared that, on account of the reception of certain persons as nuns of your said monastery, several sums of money were received by the Abbess and Convent by way of covenant, reward and compact, not without stain of <mark>the pravity of simony</mark> and, if it were so, to the peril of your souls <small> Eileen Edna Power, <a name="MLEN" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#MLEN"><cite title="source">Medieval English Nunneries</cite></a> (1922) 21</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
